<a name="9">[9]</a> <a href="#9" id=9>b) Adaptability.</a>
<a name="10">[10]</a> <a href="#10" id=10>(5) Output (Summary).</a>
<a name="11">[11]</a> <a href="#11" id=11>A summary should match the interests of readers.</a>
<a name="12">[12]</a> <a href="#12" id=12>c) Completeness.</a>
<a name="13">[13]</a> <a href="#13" id=13>c) Interactivity.</a>
<a name="14">[14]</a> <a href="#14" id=14>b) Cognitive level.</a>
<a name="15">[15]</a> <a href="#15" id=15>A summary should match the reader's cognitive level.</a>
<a name="16">[16]</a> <a href="#16" id=16>A summarization system should be improvable during use, and be able to adapt to readers' updates and adapt to new representations (especially on the same topic).</a>
<a name="17">[17]</a> <a href="#17" id=17>This also implies that a summarizer should be able to interact with readers so that it can select the appropriate representations (e.g., sentences) and use the representations that the reader is familiar with.</a>
<a name="18">[18]</a> <a href="#18" id=18>Further, it should interact with other people (including authors) to get more concepts and rules, and with the systems to get more information.</a>
<a name="19">[19]</a> <a href="#19" id=19>The core representations and the relations between them should be reserved in summary.</a>
<a name="20">[20]</a> <a href="#20" id=20>Readers' comments and previous reading behaviors (e.g., the often clicked hyperlinks) reflect interests.</a>
<a name="21">[21]</a> <a href="#21" id=21>Therefore, concepts at the reader's cognitive level should be selected.</a>
